    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-02-09T13:34:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-02-09T13:34:00-05:00" n="130"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d130">
                <head>130. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Morocco</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d130fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 771.5622/1-2762. Secret. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MCSH1"
                            >McClintic</persName>, cleared by Whitfield (<gloss target="#t_DOD1"
                            >DOD</gloss>), and approved by <persName corresp="#p_WW3"
                            >Witman</persName>. Repeated to Madrid, Paris, CINCEUR, and <gloss
                            target="#t_CINCSAC1">CINCSAC</gloss> for <gloss target="#t_POLAD1"
                            >POLAD</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-02-09T13:34:00-05:00">February 9, 1962, 1:34 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1152. <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>’s reply to <gloss target="#t_NSAM1"
                        >NSAM</gloss> 121<note n="1" xml:id="d130fn1">The reply, a memorandum from
                        Battle to <persName corresp="#p_BMG2">Bundy</persName>, February 5, is
                        ibid., <gloss target="#t_SS1">S/S</gloss>-<gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 72 D 316, <gloss target="#t_NSAM1"
                        >NSAM</gloss>s.</note> (copy by pouch) reviewed principal changes in
                    situation <gloss target="#t_RMAF1">RMAF</gloss> since Sept, noting possible
                    imminent acceptance heavy Soviet equipment and technicians (<gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 1268).<note n="2" xml:id="d130fn2">See
                            <ref target="#d129fn1">footnote 1, Document 129</ref>.</note> Concluded
                    by recommending we: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>hear again from <persName corresp="#p_BHA2">Balafrej</persName>, once
                            he has talked to King. Presuming he will reaffirm his previous
                            statements we should</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>instruct Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BPW2">Bonsal</persName> to
                            insist on an audience with King, explain we consider our assistance to
                            Morocco over past year poorly rewarded by this simultaneous recourse to
                            significant Soviet military aid and request his explanation.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Noted that while such competition (with Soviets) would create many problems we
                    realize importance our other objectives in Morocco make it highly dangerous to
                    abandon this field to Soviets and that continuing military assistance would
                    hopefully exercise limiting effect on amount Soviet aid King might feel he
                    needed to accept.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RD3">
                            <hi rend="strong">Rusk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
